[3] Malaysia
Date: 27 Jun 2016
Source: Channel NewsAsia [edited]
http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/asiapacific/measles-cases-in-malaysia/2908344.html


As of 1st week of June, the number of measles cases reported throughout Malaysia increased by 340 percent to 873, compared to 197 during the corresponding period last year [2015], said Health Department director-general Dr Noor Hisham Abdullah said on Sunday [26 Jun 2016].

In a statement which was uploaded on his Facebook page, he said the increase in cases was because the children were not immunized against the disease. Majority of the cases involved private homes (63.6 percent) followed by institutions (28.8 percent) and the community (7.6 percent).

"In 2015, there were 1318 cases of measles with 2 deaths, and this year [2016], there have not been any deaths," he said. Dr Noor Hisham said 66 outbreaks were reported during the 1st week of June [2016], a 5-fold increase compared to the corresponding period last year [2015]. "In 2014, there were only 11 reported cases of measles (first week of June) and increased to 57 cases in 2015."

In the case of chicken pox, Dr Noor Hisham said 109 cases were reported this year [2016], a 34.7 percent drop compared to the 167 in 2015 and 125 in 2014. No deaths from chicken pox were reported in the last 3 years. A majority of cases this year involve institutions (90 percent) such as nurseries, kindergartens, day care centers and detention centers.

He said measles and chickenpox were vaccine preventable diseases spread via the air and direct contact to an infected person's fluid droplets. Immunization against measles would be given to children between 9 and 12 months while chicken pox was not included in the National Immunization Program.


--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The previous ProMED post on measles in Malaysia reported that the Pahang Health Department has confirmed that the incidence of measles in the state has risen to 29 cases as of 24 Jun 2016, while this report states 873 cases. The discrepancy could be due to state incidence vs country-wide incidence reported here. Regardless, the number of cases is increasing significantly over the 2015 case numbers.

See map of Malaysia at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4317125,147. - Mod.LK]

